		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			This is perhaps the best class balancing thread I have seen yet, no matter which class.  Why?  Because Xalmat understands that the key to class balancing is NOT big upgrades.  The key to re-balancing the mage class (and the shaman class also) are subtle changes across the board.  The problem with a big upgrade in one thing or another is it has to much chance of throwing the class out of balance more then it is.  By make smaller changes to all aspects of the class (spell damage, spell cost, pet heals) while added in abilities that were missed (elemental pet focus) then you achieve much better chance of having true class balancing, not a quick short term fix which a big upgrade would bring.<br><br>The only thing I would disagree with is the damage shields.  Here I would say that Druids should have the better damage shields.  Its just part of the class.  But, the changes to duration on the mage DS is a good change.  It makes mages MGB worthwhile for the FR portion of the DS.
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							Hunter <a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=453758" target="_new">GrendalKhan Rose</a> - Forest Stalker<br>Elder <a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=586374" target=_new">Teesa Zjoquor</a> - Prophet<br><a href="http://www.thewarcouncil.us/" target="_blank">The War Council</a> - Saryrn<br><br><strike>"The general shaman consensus, however, is that the lead spell designer is so wedded to his self-delusional notions of godhood, that he refuses to admit any error unless someone up the food chain from him stuffs a change down his throat." - Chutoi Dogslobber</strike>
							</div>
								
